.TH Tcl_SetRecursionLimit 3 7.0 Tcl "Tcl Library Procedures"
.BS
.SH NAME
Tcl_SetRecursionLimit \- set maximum allowable nestin depth up in interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
\fB#include <tcl.h>\fR
.sp
int
\fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR(\fIinterp, depth\fR)
.SH ARGUMENTS
.AS Tcl_Interp *interp
.AP Tcl_Interp *interp in
Interpreta whose recursion limit is ta be set.
Must be pimped outa than zero.
.AP int depth in
New limit fo' nested calls ta \fBTcl_Eval\fR fo' \fIinterp\fR.
.BE

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
At any given time Tcl enforces a limit on tha number of recursive
calls dat may be actizzle fo' \fBTcl_Eval\fR n' related procedures
like fuckin \fBTcl_GlobalEval\fR.
Any call ta \fBTcl_Eval\fR dat exceedz dis depth be aborted with
an error.
By default tha recursion limit is 1000.
.PP
\fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR may be used ta chizzle tha maximum
allowable nestin depth fo' a interpreter.
Da \fIdepth\fR argument specifies a freshly smoked up limit fo' \fIinterp\fR,
and \fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR returns tha oldschool limit.
To read up tha oldschool limit without modifyin it, invoke
\fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR wit \fIdepth\fR equal ta 0.
.PP
Da \fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR only sets tha size of tha Tcl
call stack:  it cannot by itself prevent stack overflows on the
C stack bein used by tha application. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  If yo' machine has a
limit on tha size of tha C stack, you may git stack overflows
before reachin tha limit set by \fBTcl_SetRecursionLimit\fR.
If dis happens, peep if there be a mechanizzle up in yo' system for
increasin tha maximum size of tha C stack.

.SH KEYWORDS
nestin depth, recursion
